WEBVTT

00:01.335 --> 00:04.296
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:04.296 --> 00:08.634
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:08.634 --> 00:11.803
- My name is Gage Mason,
and I'm 19 years old.

00:11.803 --> 00:13.263
When I was in sixth grade,

00:13.263 --> 00:15.557
I was diagnosed
with narcolepsy.

00:15.557 --> 00:18.477
<i>Every job that I've had, I've</i>
<i>fallen asleep at some point,</i>

00:18.477 --> 00:21.396
but I've never fallen asleep
making a blade before.

00:21.396 --> 00:24.483
- My name is Frank Sausto
from the Bronx,

00:24.483 --> 00:26.902
and I'm a plumber
by day at a zoo.

00:26.902 --> 00:29.363
<i>I only got four years'</i>
<i>experience,</i>

00:29.363 --> 00:31.740
<i>but I know I can</i>
<i>make good blades.</i>

00:31.740 --> 00:33.367
I just want the rest
of the world to know.

00:33.367 --> 00:34.826
I hope I don't get sent home
the first round.

00:34.826 --> 00:36.203
That would suck.

00:36.203 --> 00:38.247
<i>- My name is Corey Soper.</i>

00:38.247 --> 00:40.082
<i>I'm from St. John,</i>
<i>U. S. Virgin Islands,</i>

00:40.082 --> 00:42.042
and I'm 30...

00:42.042 --> 00:43.043
[bleep].

00:43.043 --> 00:46.588
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:46.588 --> 00:48.590
<i>Uhh...</i>

00:48.590 --> 00:51.009
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:51.009 --> 00:53.303
<i>I think I'm 35.</i>

00:53.303 --> 00:56.098
<i>- My name is Tony Penruth.</i>
<i>I'm 56 years old.</i>

00:56.098 --> 00:58.308
I was a SWAT sniper
for about eight years.

00:58.308 --> 01:00.978
<i>I haven't decided what</i>
<i>I'm gonna do with the $10,000</i>

01:00.978 --> 01:04.273
when I win it, but I'm sure
the wife's gonna let me know.

01:04.273 --> 01:06.525
[chuckles]

01:06.525 --> 01:09.111
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the Forge.

01:09.111 --> 01:11.238
You're here to engage
in three rounds

01:11.238 --> 01:12.739
of edged weapon-making
competition

01:12.739 --> 01:14.575
specifically designed to test

01:14.575 --> 01:16.410
every aspect
of your capabilities.

01:16.410 --> 01:18.620
At the end of
each of our rounds,

01:18.620 --> 01:21.081
you'll be presenting your work
to our panel of expert judges.

01:21.081 --> 01:23.000
These are the men
who determine which of you

01:23.000 --> 01:24.793
will be the next
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:24.793 --> 01:26.920
and also leave here
with that check for ten grand,

01:26.920 --> 01:28.630
so let's meet them now.

01:28.630 --> 01:30.716
Two-time
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:30.716 --> 01:32.718
and fan favorite, Ben Abbott.

01:32.718 --> 01:35.596
Historic weapons re-creation
specialist, David Baker.

01:35.596 --> 01:39.266
Edged weapon specialist,
Doug Marcaida.

01:39.266 --> 01:42.019
All right, gents, in your first
round of competition today,

01:42.019 --> 01:43.729
you'll be using these.

01:43.729 --> 01:46.648
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:46.648 --> 01:50.277
These are 50-caliber,
flintlock, single shot,

01:50.277 --> 01:53.572
black powder Trapper Pistols

01:53.572 --> 01:55.449
that you will use
to forge signature blades

01:55.449 --> 01:57.284
in your signature style.

01:57.284 --> 01:59.661
<i>- [sighs]</i>

01:59.661 --> 02:03.290
<i>Flintlock pistols, what are we</i>
<i>gonna do with these things?</i>

02:03.290 --> 02:06.251
It doesn't look like
there's any steel in them.

02:06.251 --> 02:08.170
- Keep in mind that
in the second round

02:08.170 --> 02:09.838
you'll be putting
handles on your blades,

02:09.838 --> 02:11.715
turning them into
fully functional weapons

02:11.715 --> 02:13.634
that will be tested
for strength and durability

02:13.634 --> 02:15.552
<i>in a rifle buttstock chop</i>

02:15.552 --> 02:17.763
and for sharpness
in another fan favorite,

02:17.763 --> 02:19.806
the apple slice.

02:19.806 --> 02:21.642
You will have ten minutes
to work on your designs.

02:21.642 --> 02:23.977
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

02:23.977 --> 02:26.063
Good luck, bladesmiths.

02:26.063 --> 02:28.065
Your ten-minute
design window starts...

02:28.065 --> 02:30.942
now.

02:30.942 --> 02:32.903
Ben, what do these guys
have to be careful of

02:32.903 --> 02:34.946
as they forge these barrels,

02:34.946 --> 02:36.865
which is probably
the only usable steel

02:36.865 --> 02:38.867
on the entire gun, correct?

02:38.867 --> 02:40.786
- Yeah. These barrels are made
of chrome alloy steel,

02:40.786 --> 02:43.872
and the chromium
has tenacious oxides.

02:43.872 --> 02:46.333
It makes forge welding
not impossible,

02:46.333 --> 02:48.043
but just a little
more difficult.

02:48.043 --> 02:49.086
You have to
make sure everything

02:49.086 --> 02:50.921
is as clean as possible.

02:50.921 --> 02:52.673
<i>- My anxiety's</i>
<i>through the roof.</i>

02:52.673 --> 02:54.049
I'm panicking trying
to get a game plan going.

02:54.049 --> 02:56.259
Everything's going
through my head.

02:56.259 --> 02:58.136
I want something that will chop
and something that will slice,

02:58.136 --> 03:01.306
so what's better than
a competition chopper?

03:01.306 --> 03:03.600
<i>I got into making blades</i>
<i>a few years ago</i>

03:03.600 --> 03:05.519
<i>pretty much out of fun.</i>

03:05.519 --> 03:07.437
<i>I always wanted to have,</i>
<i>like, a man-cave</i>

03:07.437 --> 03:10.107
<i>with, like, a nice wall</i>
<i>of all my work.</i>

03:10.107 --> 03:14.861
You know, man [bleep].

03:14.861 --> 03:17.489
<i>- For this challenge, I'm</i>
<i>designing a drop point hunter.</i>

03:17.489 --> 03:20.242
<i>It tends to be a little</i>
<i>more balanced in the hand.</i>

03:20.242 --> 03:22.369
<i>It's just a very</i>
<i>comfortable knife to use.</i>

03:22.369 --> 03:24.996
<i>I started out</i>
<i>as a United States Marine.</i>

03:24.996 --> 03:27.165
I got out of the Marine Corp.

03:27.165 --> 03:28.917
<i>Didn't want to have a boss,</i>
<i>so I became a farrier.</i>

03:28.917 --> 03:30.627
<i>Got tired of bending</i>
<i>over for a living,</i>

03:30.627 --> 03:32.087
so I became a police officer,

03:32.087 --> 03:33.839
<i>and I'm getting</i>
<i>ready to retire,</i>

03:33.839 --> 03:36.049
and I'll be full-time
as a bladesmith.

03:36.049 --> 03:38.885
- Are these
pistol barrels rifled?

03:38.885 --> 03:40.345
both: Yes.

03:40.345 --> 03:41.721
- Okay, so there's
a complication

03:41.721 --> 03:43.306
that our smiths
have to get around

03:43.306 --> 03:44.975
because the rifling
in that barrel

03:44.975 --> 03:46.810
can't just be mashed
together, correct?

03:46.810 --> 03:48.145
- No, yeah, that's right.
You could get cold shuts

03:48.145 --> 03:49.729
because it's
pretty square edges.

03:49.729 --> 03:54.109
- I'm designing
a modified chef knife,

03:54.109 --> 03:56.278
<i>just because</i>
<i>it's a fairly easy shape</i>

03:56.278 --> 03:58.280
<i>for me to knock out.</i>

03:58.280 --> 04:00.449
<i>I was actually born</i>
<i>in Connecticut,</i>

04:00.449 --> 04:04.327
but my parents bought a boat

04:04.327 --> 04:07.289
and then they decided
to move to St. John.

04:07.289 --> 04:09.499
<i>I actually still</i>
<i>live on a boat,</i>

04:09.499 --> 04:11.710
<i>so that's just sort of</i>
<i>second nature to me,</i>

04:11.710 --> 04:15.338
and it's cheaper
than paying rent.

04:15.338 --> 04:19.134
- I'm gonna make a simple
sheepsfoot style blade.

04:19.134 --> 04:21.094
<i>I'm gonna use the barrel</i>
<i>because it's obviously</i>

04:21.094 --> 04:22.929
<i>the largest part</i>
<i>of steel on the gun,</i>

04:22.929 --> 04:24.848
<i>and because I can use it</i>

04:24.848 --> 04:26.892
<i>to make a relatively</i>
<i>flat piece of steel.</i>

04:26.892 --> 04:29.519
I've used very similar
pistols like this before,

04:29.519 --> 04:31.730
so I think I have an edge
over the competition

04:31.730 --> 04:33.982
<i>because I know how</i>
<i>to disassemble them quickly.</i>

04:33.982 --> 04:35.692
- Your design window
is now closed.

04:35.692 --> 04:38.570
Your three-hour forge
time starts...now.

04:38.570 --> 04:41.990
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:41.990 --> 04:45.994
- Oh, poor, poor gun.
Bye.

04:45.994 --> 04:47.788
Peace.

04:47.788 --> 04:49.956
- This is gonna be
an interesting challenge.

04:49.956 --> 04:51.958
- It looks like Tony
might be cutting

04:51.958 --> 04:54.169
the back end off that barrel,
cutting the breach off.

04:54.169 --> 04:56.630
<i>- I don't know exactly what</i>
<i>kind of metal the barrel is,</i>

04:56.630 --> 04:58.423
but I know it's gonna be

04:58.423 --> 05:00.634
a lower-carbon steel
being black powdered.

05:00.634 --> 05:02.260
<i>You're just not running with</i>
<i>the pressures that you are</i>

05:02.260 --> 05:04.596
with a higher caliber,
modern day firearm.

05:04.596 --> 05:06.431
<i>The first thing</i>
<i>you got to do</i>

05:06.431 --> 05:08.600
is get the thing down
into billet form.

05:08.600 --> 05:11.061
<i>I'm gonna collapse</i>
<i>the tube down on itself,</i>

05:11.061 --> 05:12.896
<i>make two layers out of it,</i>

05:12.896 --> 05:15.190
and I'm gonna forge weld this.

05:15.190 --> 05:17.442
I'm gonna be doing
multiple layers on this

05:17.442 --> 05:19.277
because I'm afraid
I'm gonna get an inclusion

05:19.277 --> 05:21.238
when I close up the barrel
with the rifling.

05:21.238 --> 05:22.781
So the more I pull this,

05:22.781 --> 05:24.366
it's hopefully going
to be getting rid

05:24.366 --> 05:26.034
of the possibility
of some inclusions.

05:26.034 --> 05:29.454
<i>My strategy today</i>
<i>is take my time.</i>

05:29.454 --> 05:33.291
Slow is smooth.
Smooth is fast.

05:33.291 --> 05:36.753
- I cut my hand on a barnacle
the day before I came here,

05:36.753 --> 05:39.923
and this gauze makes holding
a hammer in my right hand

05:39.923 --> 05:42.801
<i>extremely difficult,</i>
<i>unfortunately,</i>

05:42.801 --> 05:44.886
so I feed it over
the power hammer

05:44.886 --> 05:46.847
<i>to do the initial forge weld.</i>

05:46.847 --> 05:48.765
That power hammer no joke.

05:48.765 --> 05:51.226
- He's got one forge weld
folded over.

05:51.226 --> 05:53.103
He squished it flat,

05:53.103 --> 05:54.646
and I don't think that
forge weld is holding.

05:54.646 --> 05:56.731
He's obviously fighting it.

05:56.731 --> 05:58.692
<i>- The power hammer is just</i>
<i>way too aggressive.</i>

05:58.692 --> 06:01.444
I realize it's drawn out
way too much,

06:01.444 --> 06:04.030
<i>and I have a bunch</i>
<i>of delaminations.</i>

06:04.030 --> 06:06.324
[bleep].

06:06.324 --> 06:09.744
<i>I have to just continuously</i>
<i>start folding this billet</i>

06:09.744 --> 06:13.039
and trying to consolidate
the steel into a solid block.

06:13.039 --> 06:14.833
<i>Otherwise I'm screwed.</i>

06:14.833 --> 06:18.461
This could be [bleep].

06:18.461 --> 06:21.089
<i>- I've never made a knife out</i>
<i>of a pistol before,</i>

06:21.089 --> 06:24.134
<i>but the first thing I want to</i>
<i>do is cut this barrel</i>

06:24.134 --> 06:25.969
right down the middle,

06:25.969 --> 06:28.638
<i>getting that thing</i>
<i>opened up and flat.</i>

06:28.638 --> 06:32.601
- Big Blue is smashing
the heck out of that billet.

06:32.601 --> 06:34.102
<i>- The power hammer?</i>

06:34.102 --> 06:36.146
It got some balls to it,
let me tell you.

06:36.146 --> 06:39.107
I step on that pedal and,
boom, it is moving this metal

06:39.107 --> 06:41.026
like I've never seen
metal move before.

06:41.026 --> 06:43.528
- We've seen it happen,
that Big Blue hypnosis.

06:43.528 --> 06:45.071
Smiths get on there
and that hammer just goes

06:45.071 --> 06:46.615
boom, boom, boom on that steel.

06:46.615 --> 06:48.366
You feel it in your chest.

06:48.366 --> 06:50.118
Pretty soon you've got
this long, skinny,

06:50.118 --> 06:52.162
flat piece of metal.

06:52.162 --> 06:54.205
- How you doing, brother?
- All right.

06:54.205 --> 06:56.249
- Keep on going.

06:56.249 --> 06:59.419
- Frank is definitely
is definitely a New Yorker.

06:59.419 --> 07:01.671
You can tell instantly
from his accent.

07:01.671 --> 07:04.633
- Finally got that knot out.
Jeez.

07:04.633 --> 07:07.469
- I'm definitely not a city
boy, that's for sure.

07:07.469 --> 07:10.430
I like to hunt, fish,
do things outside.

07:10.430 --> 07:12.432
<i>If I had a choice</i>
<i>between the two,</i>

07:12.432 --> 07:15.727
I would take living out in
the middle of nowhere any day.

07:15.727 --> 07:17.437
<i>I'm having a lot of trouble</i>

07:17.437 --> 07:19.356
getting this gun barrel
split in half.

07:19.356 --> 07:20.899
<i>The edges want to curl up</i>

07:20.899 --> 07:23.860
and want to fold in
on each other,

07:23.860 --> 07:27.822
<i>and can cause cold shuts</i>
<i>and delams.</i>

07:27.822 --> 07:31.368
- Gage still hasn't even
flattened out that barrel.

07:31.368 --> 07:34.454
I just don't know what's
going on in his process.

07:34.454 --> 07:36.956
<i>- If I can't get this gun</i>
<i>barrel split open,</i>

07:36.956 --> 07:38.958
I'm gonna have a piece
of unusable steel.

07:38.958 --> 07:41.252
- One hour has elapsed!

07:41.252 --> 07:43.004
You have just
two hours remaining

07:43.004 --> 07:44.631
to finish your blades!

07:44.631 --> 07:46.508
Now, I notice that Tony,

07:46.508 --> 07:48.468
he was on the power hammer
a couple of times,

07:48.468 --> 07:51.763
but most of his work has been
done on the hammer and anvil.

07:51.763 --> 07:53.181
<i>- I'm gonna do well</i>
<i>in this competition</i>

07:53.181 --> 07:55.642
because I forge my blades.

07:55.642 --> 07:57.227
I work the metal hot.

07:57.227 --> 08:00.063
- Wow, Tony's going
for another fold.

08:00.063 --> 08:01.981
This is his fifth fold?

08:01.981 --> 08:03.817
- Yeah, I think so.

08:03.817 --> 08:06.111
<i>- I believe I got</i>
<i>64 layers out of it.</i>

08:06.111 --> 08:08.822
<i>Everything's starting to</i>
<i>unfold the way I imagined it.</i>

08:08.822 --> 08:14.577
I'm comfortable with
what's going on right now.

08:14.577 --> 08:17.622
<i>- Right now, the forge welds</i>
<i>are coming apart.</i>

08:17.622 --> 08:21.334
That's a major problem.
It's just sucky.

08:21.334 --> 08:23.211
- Corey tried to press
everything together,

08:23.211 --> 08:25.088
and it looked to me
like he pressed parts,

08:25.088 --> 08:26.631
and it opened up other parts.

08:26.631 --> 08:28.633
- Ahhh!

08:28.633 --> 08:31.553
My arm's getting tired,
and time's running out,

08:31.553 --> 08:34.639
<i>but as long as I can get</i>
<i>the welds to stick,</i>

08:34.639 --> 08:37.475
<i>I know I can get a blade</i>
<i>shaped out quickly.</i>

08:37.475 --> 08:40.061
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:40.061 --> 08:43.356
<i>- Man, it's intense.</i>
<i>I'm feeling the pressure.</i>

08:43.356 --> 08:45.233
I'm used to working
in my shop by myself

08:45.233 --> 08:47.152
where I'm comfortable.

08:47.152 --> 08:49.070
<i>I can take a break.</i>
<i>I can crack a beer.</i>

08:49.070 --> 08:50.989
Here, there's none of that.

08:50.989 --> 08:53.950
- That's an interesting belly
in Frank's blade there.

08:53.950 --> 08:56.745
- It's a great chopper.
I like that shape, man.

08:56.745 --> 08:58.413
<i>- I got a three-year-old</i>
<i>daughter, Isabella.</i>

08:58.413 --> 08:59.914
<i>She always comes down</i>
<i>to my shop</i>

08:59.914 --> 09:01.416
<i>with her little</i>
<i>plastic hammers.</i>

09:01.416 --> 09:03.543
Always wants to be involved.

09:03.543 --> 09:07.130
You know, maybe she'll be
my little helper one day.

09:07.130 --> 09:09.674
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:09.674 --> 09:12.927
<i>- I've decided to abandon the</i>
<i>whole flattening it out thing</i>

09:12.927 --> 09:14.846
because the edges
are curled too bad.

09:14.846 --> 09:17.265
- Gage is over
at the welding station,

09:17.265 --> 09:20.435
and it looks like he's got a
flat stock of maybe mild steel

09:20.435 --> 09:23.021
that he's welding
to his blade right now.

09:23.021 --> 09:27.484
He's laying it into that taco,
but just on the very end,

09:27.484 --> 09:29.694
as if he's trying
to create a tang.

09:29.694 --> 09:32.072
- It's a risky move to weld
a piece of mild steel

09:32.072 --> 09:33.865
into a blade,

09:33.865 --> 09:35.867
<i>but because it's</i>
<i>in a non-critical area,</i>

09:35.867 --> 09:38.411
I think it'll do just fine
for the tang.

09:38.411 --> 09:41.873
I'm exhausted.

09:41.873 --> 09:44.918
<i>Because of my medication</i>
<i>that I take for my narcolepsy,</i>

09:44.918 --> 09:47.295
<i>my blood pressure</i>
<i>and heart rate's always high.</i>

09:47.295 --> 09:49.339
I just feel like
I'm gonna pass out.

09:49.339 --> 09:51.091
- All right,
you want to take a blow

09:51.091 --> 09:52.675
over here
for a couple minutes?

09:52.675 --> 09:54.094
- Yeah, that would
probably be good.

09:54.094 --> 09:56.179
<i>I really don't want to quit,</i>

09:56.179 --> 09:59.182
but I know that I can't be
on the Forge floor now.

09:59.182 --> 10:01.768
- Gage is walking off
the Forge floor.

10:01.768 --> 10:04.104
- He looks pretty overheated.

10:04.104 --> 10:05.730
- Two hours has elapsed!

10:05.730 --> 10:07.524
That means, you just have

10:07.524 --> 10:10.360
60 tiny, little minutes
to finish your work!

10:10.360 --> 10:12.612
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:12.612 --> 10:15.740
<i>- I'm not freaking out</i>
<i>on this at all.</i>

10:15.740 --> 10:17.742
I'm way out
in front of everybody.

10:17.742 --> 10:20.995
The hardest part is getting
the heat treat right.

10:20.995 --> 10:23.206
<i>That can be challenging</i>
<i>when you're not dealing</i>

10:23.206 --> 10:25.667
with a metal that you know.

10:25.667 --> 10:27.127
- Boom.
- There we go.

10:27.127 --> 10:28.962
Tony just quenched.

10:28.962 --> 10:32.382
- It's not hard.

10:32.382 --> 10:35.593
Nope, nope.
Got to get it hotter.

10:35.593 --> 10:40.598
Okay, strike one.

10:40.598 --> 10:43.393
- Corey has just quenched.
- I see Tony looking at Corey

10:43.393 --> 10:45.895
now wondering how
hard Corey's blade got.

10:45.895 --> 10:47.689
- Oh, no, no,
no, no, no, no, no, no.

10:47.689 --> 10:50.108
<i>This is mushy as crap.</i>

10:50.108 --> 10:52.318
What? That doesn't
make any sense.

10:52.318 --> 10:54.696
- Oh, he's going back in.
- Oh, yeah.

10:54.696 --> 10:57.448
- He didn't like it.

10:57.448 --> 10:59.701
- And Tony's back
in the quench.

10:59.701 --> 11:01.452
- [bleep].

11:01.452 --> 11:02.829
It's still not hard.

11:02.829 --> 11:04.998
<i>You've got to be kidding me.</i>

11:04.998 --> 11:07.750
- Going in again?
- Didn't harden.

11:07.750 --> 11:10.086
- That's confidence inspiring.

11:10.086 --> 11:13.631
<i>I'm gonna quench again.</i>

11:13.631 --> 11:16.009
This time I get it
even hotter.

